#Text=Last Ottoman dies , aged 91
#Text=Thursday , April 5 , 2012
#Text=Sultan Vahideddin ( Mehmed VI ) departing from the backdoor of the Dolmabahçe Palace in Istanbul in 1922 .
#Text=Map of the Ottoman Empire at the end of the 16th century .
#Text=Image : lynxxx .
#Text=Fatma Neslişah Osmanoğlu , who was the last Ottoman royal born during the Ottoman Empire , died at age 91 , reportedly from a heart attack , Monday and was buried in Istanbul , Turkey .
#Text=Neslişah was both the granddaughter of Sultan Vahdettin , who was the last Ottoman Emperor , and Abdülmecid II , who was the last Ottoman Caliph .

#Text=Neslişah was also the wife of Egyptian Prince Muhammad Abdel Moneim , who was the head of Egypt ’ s regency for a short while before the revolution in which Muhammad Naguib and Gamal Abdel Nasser removed the monarchy from power .
#Text=This was the second monarchy removed by revolution and sent into exile that Neslişah had personally experienced .
#Text=When Neslişah was born on February 4 , 1921 , cannons were fired to spread the news and she was registered in the family records , the last child of the Ottoman line to be registered .
#Text=She was born just two years before Mustafa Kemal Atatürk founded modern Turkey .
#Text=The Turkish revolution brought the formal end of the Ottoman dynasty .
#Text=The Ottomans had ruled for 600 years .
#Text=At the peak of the Empire , the family 's rule stretched across the Middle East and North Africa , as well as to Eastern Europe .
#Text=As a young girl , Neslişah left Turkey for exile with her relatives after the royal family was banished .
#Text=In 1940 , she married the Prince in Egypt .
#Text=The Prince was head of the regency for under a year between 1952 and 1953 .
#Text=She was briefly under arrest with her husband , when he was accused of conspiring against Nasser , before they were sent into exile .
#Text=As an exile in France , she longed to be repatriated to her homeland and the city of Istanbul where she is now buried .
#Text=She told a biographer , Murat Bardakçı , " My mother had friends who would go to Istanbul .
